While bulls point to a solid F4Q beat and a conservative FY26 guide, bears argue F4Q largely benefitted from an artificial pullforward of spend and guidance assumptions do not look conservative. We remain on the sidelines as consensus estimates coming down likely weighs on shares. EW.
BILL beat F4Q consensus with a \(0.165\%\) AP/AR take rate, \(13\%\) Integrated Platform TPV YoY growth, 6,300 Integrated Platform net adds, and a \(14.7\%\) operating margin
But, FY26 guidance missed consensus with \(13\%\) Core Revenue YoY growth (vs. \(15\%\) ) and \(15.8\%\) margin (vs. \(16.4\%\) )
TPV artificially benefitted from spending pullforward ahead of tariffs, suggesting TPV per customer declined YoY on an adjusted basis
Management's FY26 assumptions - flat TPV/customer and similar AP/AR take rate expansion as FY25 - do not appear particularly conservative
Forward consensus estimates coming down on this print and questions around the conservatism of FY26 guidance likely weigh on shares T+1

BILL reported a solid F4Q with multiple key metrics beating consensus estimates: 1) AP/AR take rate of \(0.185\%\) vs. consensus' estimate of \(0.164\%\) ; 2) Integrated Platform TPV YoY growth of \(0.13\%\) vs. consensus' \(9\%\) ; 3) Integrated Platform net adds of 6,300 vs. consensus' \(5.00\) ; 4) Operating income margin of \(14.7\%\) vs. consensus' \(12.2\%\) . BILL also announced a new share buyback program of \(300 million\) (\~7% of BILL's current market cap). The outperformance on the AP/AR take rate side came from strong international payments volume and AP Card adoption. New customer momentum remains robust, especially within the accounting channel, which grew \(24\%\) YoY. On the TPV side, management called out how Q4 artificially benefitted from customers pulling forward spend ahead of tariffs. Integrated Platform TPV per customer was flat YoY despite benefitting from the spending pullforward, which implies TPV per customer was likely down YoY when removing the pullforward benefit.
Looking forward, initial FY26 guidance of Core Revenue YoY growth of \(13\%\) and

operating income margin of \(15.8\%\) both came in below consensus' estimates of \(15\%\) and \(16.4\%\) , respectively. Within the mid- point of guidance are imbedded assumptions of flat TPV per customer YoY growth, a similar AP/AR take rate expansion as FY25's 0.4bps, and a lower Spend & Expense take rate ( \(\sim 250\) bps). Management noted these assumptions are 'prudent' and not necessarily 'conservative' as Q4 benefitted from the spending pullforward and Spend & Expense take rate is now facing headwinds from a mix shift away from the higher monetizing advertising and T&E categories, which are under pressure from tariffs.

The debate on the stock will now center on how 'prudent' management is being around the FY26 guidance. While there is an exciting emerging product cycle with Advanced ACH / Supplier Payments Plus, it is still very early days and likely takes time before meaningfully contributing to take rate. With Q4's AP/AR take rate also likely artificially benefitting from additional international payments ahead of tariffs, a similar AP/AR take rate expansion in FY26 as FY25 does not screen as particularly conservative to us. Furthermore, FY26 guidance is assuming TPV per customer slightly recovers to flattish growth following Q4's likely negative YoY growth rate when adjusting for the pullforward benefit. Bottom line, we do not see the midpoint of FY26's guidance as particularly conservative. As such, we remain on the sidelines awaiting greater evidence of a growth recovery. Forward consensus estimates coming down on this print and questions around the conservatism of FY26 guidance likely weigh on shares T+1.
Macro Uncertainty Overshadows an Improved Strategy
Key: Historical Stock Performance Current Stock Price Price Target

A volatile and uncertain macro environment likely keeps BILL's key growth metrics of Total Payment Volume (TPV) and take rate constrained, limiting upside to estimates. With a lack of positive catalysts on the horizon, we prefer to be Equal-weight until we can garner greater confidence in improvement in growth.

Revenue grows at a \(11\%\) CAGR through CY29 to reach \(\) 2.4B\$ Faster topline and robust demand warrants higher spend resulting in less leverage and FCF margin of \(\sim 21\%\) . Our bull case of \(\) 65\$ assumes a 21x EV/CY29 FCF multiple discounted back at a \(13.5\%\) WACC. \(\) 65\$ implies \(\sim 4x\) EV/CY26 Sales and \(\sim 20x\) EV/CY26 FCF.

We model a \(9\%\) revenue CAGR through CY29 to reach \(\) 2.1B\$ . Op margin improvement to \(\sim 24\%\) in CY29e. A 17x EV/CY29 FCF discounted back at \(13.5\%\) WACC yields our \(\) 55\$ price target. Our PT of \(\) 55\$ implies \(\sim 3x\) EV/CY26 Sales and \(\sim 15x\) EV/CY26 FCF.

Revenue grows at a \(5\%\) CAGR through CY29 to reach \(\) 1.8B\$ . Slower growth warrants a pull back in spend, providing more leverage and FCF margin of \(\sim 20\%\) . Our bear case of \(\) 30\$ assumes a 12x EV/CY32 FCF multiple discounted back at a \(13.5\%\) WACC. \(\) 30\$ implies \(\sim 2x\) EV/CY26 Sales and \(\sim 10x\) EV/CY26 FCF.
